In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims March as Women's History Month. He acknowledges the contributions of American women throughout history in various fields such as social and economic justice, science, art, literature, and foreign policy. The president recognizes the struggles women have faced and continue to face, including workplace discrimination, sexual assault, and the gender pay gap. He highlights his administration's efforts to support women, such as signing the Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act and implementing the Affordable Care Act to prevent gender-based insurance discrimination. Additionally, he mentions initiatives to promote women's participation in STEM fields, extend labor protections to homecare workers, and combat sexual assault on college campuses. The president calls for the celebration of International Women's Day on March 8 and encourages Americans to learn more about the achievements of women in history.